## 3. 🗄️ Database Design (Schema)

Since this is a DBMS project, your professors will focus heavily on how you structured your tables. Your database is hosted on **PostgreSQL** via Supabase. 

You have two primary tables:

### **Table 1: `bookings` (The Core Entity)**
Tracks all currently occupied parking slots.

| Column Name | Data Type | Key Type | Purpose |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| `slot_id` | `String` / `VARCHAR` | **Primary Key** | The unique identifier for the parking bay (e.g., "A1", "C4"). Acting as a Primary Key guarantees that **two users cannot book the same slot** simultaneously (Data Integrity). |
| `customer_name` | `String` | | Name of the driver. |
| `vehicle_number` | `String` | | License plate (e.g. MH 12 AB 1234). |
| `start_time` | `Time/String`| | Time of entry. |
| `end_time` | `Time/String`| | Expected time of exit. |
| `created_at` | `Timestamp` | Default | Automatically marks exactly when the transaction occurred. |

### **Table 2: `activity_log` (The Audit Trail)**
Tracks everything that happens across the system for the Admin dashboard.

| Column Name | Data Type | Key Type | Purpose |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| `id` | `UUID` | **Primary Key** | A universally unique identifier auto-generated for each log entry. |
| `action_description` | `String/Text` | | A human-readable text string (e.g., "Admin cancelled booking for slot A1"). |
| `created_at` | `Timestamp` | Default | The chronological anchor to sort the history page newest-first. |

